<subsection xml:id="subsec-locating-a-point-using-bearing-and-distance-in-real-life-situations">
    <title>Locating a Point Using Bearing and Distance in Real Life Situations</title>
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <term>Work in groups</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Materials Needed</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                Compass, measuring tape or meter wheel, clipboards, pencils, school compound map (or blank paper for sketching).
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           In your groups, choose a starting point within the school compound (e.g., school gate, flagpole, staffroom). 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Each group will hoose 3–4 other landmarks around the school.
            
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Use the compass to determine the bearing from their starting point to each landmark.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Measure or estimate the distance between their point and each landmark. Record bearings using three-figure notation (e.g., 072°).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Create a scaled sketch map of the landmarks showing relative positions, distances and bearings.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Each group presents one of their bearings and explain how they measured it. What  challenges did you face in this activity? (e.g., compass interference)
                            What are the real-world implications of bearing (e.g., navigation, mapping, aviation).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>              
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{ Key Takeaway }</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        Bearings and distances is used to accurately determine and plot the location of an object or landmark on a map.
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Point P is <m>1300\,m</m> due west of point Q. Point R is <m>400 \, m</m> due north  of point Q. Point S is <m>1000\,m</m> due west of R. 
                Using a scale of <m>1\,m \text{ rep } 100\,cm,</m> sketch the given information and answer the following questions:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Determine the bearing of S from P. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Distance PS.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Sketch the given information:
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="sketch-bearing-distance">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \usetikzlibrary{angles,quotes} % Required for angle annotations

                        \filldraw[black] (0,0) circle (2pt) node[below right] {P};  
                        \filldraw[black] (5,0) circle (2pt) node[below right] {Q};
                        \filldraw[black] (5,4) circle (2pt) node[below right] {R};
                        \filldraw[black] (3,4) circle (2pt) node[below right] {S};

                        % Trapezium PQRS
                        \coordinate (P) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (Q) at (5,0);
                        \coordinate (R) at (5,4);
                        \coordinate (S) at (3,4);

                        \draw[thick] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- (S) -- cycle;
                        
                        \draw[black,-&gt;] (0,-1)--(0,1); 
                        \draw[black] (-1,0)--(1,0);

                        \node at (2.5,-.5) {$1300 m$};
                        \node at (5.5,2) {$400 m$};
                        \node at (4,4.5) {$1000 m$};

                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
            <p>
                The sketch when drawn to scale of  <m>1\,m \text{ rep } 100\,cm:</m>
            </p>
            <image>
                <latex-image label="scale-drawing-bearing-distance">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \usetikzlibrary{angles,quotes} % Required for angle annotations

                        \filldraw[black] (0,0) circle (2pt) node[below right] {P};  
                        \filldraw[black] (5,0) circle (2pt) node[below right] {Q};
                        \filldraw[black] (5,4) circle (2pt) node[below right] {R};
                        \filldraw[black] (3,4) circle (2pt) node[below right] {S};

                        % Trapezium PQRS
                        \coordinate (P) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (Q) at (5,0);
                        \coordinate (R) at (5,4);
                        \coordinate (S) at (3,4);
                        \coordinate (T) at (0,1);

                        \draw[thick] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- (S) -- cycle;
                        
                        \draw[black,-&gt;] (0,-1)--(0,1); 
                        \draw[black] (-1,0)--(1,0);

                        \node at (2.5,-.5) {$13 cm$};
                        \node at (5.5,2) {$4 cm$};
                        \node at (4,4.5) {$10 cm$};

                        \draw[draw=black] plot coordinates{(T)(P)(S)} pic["$ $", draw=orange, angle eccentricity=1.2, angle radius=.5cm]
                        {angle=S--P--T};; 
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
            <p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Use a compass to find the bearing of point S from Q. The bearing of S from P is <m>045^\circ.</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                       Use a ruler to measure the drawing length PS then convert your answer to the actual disatnce using the given scale. The drawing length of PS is <m>5\,cm.</m>
                        Therefore the actual distance will be <m>5 \, \times 100 \, m = 500 \, m.</m> 
                    </p>
                </li>
              </ul>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
    
    
</subsection>